{
  "doc_id": "32295",
  "text": "The cholinergic hypersensitivty theory in depression was postulated when more was known about muscarinic than nicotinic receptors (nAChRs). While much more is known now about nAChR pharmacology, few attempts have been made to explain the role of nAChRs in the inter-relationships between cholinergic systems and mood disorders [CITATION_1] . The nAChRs are expressed throughout the nervous system, and they not only exist on neuronal cell bodies and dendrites but also are located on axon terminals and are involved in multiple neurotransmitter release, including acetylcholine, DA, 5-HT, GABA, glutamate and norepinephrine [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . It is known now that the neuroendronine effects of physostigmine are mediated primarily through the activation of nAChRs, and not muscarinic receptors [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . In addition, studies characterizing the effects of smoking on mood in normal smokers suggest that while mood improves immediately after smoking, mood impairments (including dysphoria and irritability) occur between smoking episodes [CITATION_6] , and the depressive mood predicts relapse of smoking behavior [CITATION_7] . This repetitive cycle of shifting mood suggests a role for nAChRs, and may explain partly the high comorbidity between depression and nicotine dependence in both adolescents and adults [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] .",
